,Recommended,242680,22198326,"Posted: 2 April, 2016",all,Fluury,"Don't let yourself get fooled by the bright blue thumb up, this game is/was a wild train-ride which ended in a crash. Pun intended.(If U99/U100 fixes♥♥♥♥♥♥ Ill update this review.)>>Emotional backstory, if you wanna read the review, scroll down.<<You put a certain level of trust in a dev when you buy an early access game, and honestly, I thought that trust I put into Nuclear Throne and Vlambeer was well put with what they did. They communicated with the community, they did weekly dev streams and weekly updates. You really felt like you were part of the development. I have never seen any other devs do the entire early access thing this good, and to this date I hope for it to eventually be the standard.Nearing the end of 2015, it all started to get downhill. Several issues addressed by a lot of players back then were said to be fixed ""in the polishing phase"" - right now, we had the ""feature and content phase"" - so balance, bugs, crashes etc. were to be fixed by then. The problem was that the so called ""polishing phase"" never really came alongside of other expectations raised by the dev, like full-seeding-support, or other things, like balance-overhauls of areas and other things. There was an insane amount of potential for Nuclear Throne, and the community reported and helped the devs more than enough to make the fullest out of that potential.Not saying they didn't do anything, though,  there was a certain level of polish done, some bugs were fixed, some details likeravens leaving feathers added. Major crashes, some people literally being unable to play the game and other bugs though? Completely ignored. I didn't mind back then, since the game was in early access - and its completely acceptable for a game in early access to have crashes and bugs, since you know.An early access game can have bugs and crashes, since its unfinished. A released game however says that the game isdone- little bugs and crashes are supposed to be there.So, around the end of 2015, the devs further and further pushed to release, constantly threw the sentence ""we are almost done guys!"" - which was followed by an insane amount of negativity by the community. Understandably, since, as I already said, there were tons of bugs, crashes and balance issues still to be fixed. No way they'll release the game like that - that's atleast what I thought, since I still trusted Vlambeer in their decision.Until the shocking date of the 5th December - around 5 months have passed since the release. Remember that number, it'll become relevant later. That is when they announced the release of the game for both the PC and consoles, and that is when people started loosing their♥♥♥♥♥♥ The extremely negative stigma and feeling of disappointment really got onto some people, understandably, since the game is in a broken state.""uhh buddy, ya sure you didn't mean ""back then"" ? - I mean, 5 months have passed, s-surely they fi - ""Nope. Some people still cant play the game, several people still crash, and people still get a frozen screen.This is not me complaining about the broken balance of the game (which you have lots of) - but me complaining about a game said to be ""released"" to have a♥♥♥♥♥♥ton of bugs and crashes. I'm not overreacting either, you have lots of jokesters saying ""B-but, it isnt that bad!"" - Itisthat bad - Hell, one of the main reasons I stopped doing Dailies is because 30% of my daily runs end in a freeze, followed up with a death screen.And don't let me get started on the console version of the game, that version has its own set of issues like the player not being able to select their starting weapon, crown or skin - btw, these people have not even received both of the tiny updates which fixed maybe 5% of the issues available - reminder, 5 months have passed.--- And the ride is still going for both the PC Version and the console version. Both versions are still screwed, and while the changelog of Update 99 looks pretty, it's already sad that it takes over 5 months to fix insane issues.I'll put it like STAR_, an ex-Nuclear Throne Streamer said it when he streamed the game after a long pause :""Game was more stable and better 3 months ago.""------------------------------Now, the game ; Let's talk about the game, the main thing you are here I'll assume.Pros:- Fluid Controls and Game-feel.- Wide selection of Weapons.- Lots of Characters and combinations to try out.- Dailies and Weeklies (Runs where everyone has the ""same Seed"" (<- Not really since Seeds are broken.) which end up with your score (Right now : Kills.) being submitted to a leaderboard andwww.thronebutt.com)  add extra replayability and competition which encourages improvement.- Sound effects are tastier than Guy Fieri's hottest hits.Neutral:- Mediocre amount of perks upon leveling up + them not being really balanced leaves up for a very limited amount of viable perks, thus runs end up feeling the same.- Pixel art tastes differently in everyone's mouth, while I like it most of it, I wouldnt call it amazing.- Same goes for the Music. It's good if you'd ask me, but nothing too amazing.- It's a difficult game. If you are a soft-bean which wants to be spoonfed, this isn't the game for you. Can and will likely get insanely frustrating.- While Roguelike elements are there, it is not enough to make the game not feel repetitive for most at the end.-Crowns (Gameplay modifiers) are the definition of missed potential.Negative:- 30 FPS.- No widescreen Support.- Several Bugs and crashes which have been reported several times are still not fixed. Some Features even unfinished.- Late-game and perk-balance is far from a good state.** This♥♥♥♥♥♥will have a lot of Spoilers about late-game, so if you wanna explore that yourself, lemme sum it up : Expect terrible balance of both enemies and weapons.I don't know what happened to the idea of Loops, I suppose it was rushed like the entire game was. Another thing pushed back to ""we'll do that later"" - only to be ended up half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ The main idea back then was ""Less-enemies, less randomness, more Elites! The Elites are the thing making the Loops hard, har har!"" - however that transformed into ""We can't be bothered to make more Elite enemies which is why we made 6 and then just added enemies out of secret areas and left the rest pretty much as it is""The Quality of the Elite enemies we got sunk and sunk until we got nothing, too. It first started with Elite IDPD, which were cool with their own unique sprites and attacks, but however came with frustrating Insta-kills, because apparently you can only make something hard if it instantly kills you. Anyways, from these, we went to Elite-Aligators, which also instantly killed the player upon being shot, and then we went to literally two deviantart-reskins, one of them being insanely weak. That's it.Some Areas literally don't have any Elite enemies.Oh, Vans too. Sometimes unavoidable, even.""But it's a single player game, why should balance matter in that?""Because it isn't a single player game. With the addition of online-leaderboards, the player is now going for ""the best"" - which ended up with a stale Daily meta of Melee, SPC, and CoB. Maybe 15% of the Weapons in the game are viable late-game with CoB. Instead of being about ""who is better at the game?"" - Dailies are now ""Who is better at the modified game?""Oh right, Perks. We have an insanely limited amount of Perks, or called, Mutations, which are also horribly balanced. There is a certain ""elite 10"" of mutations which are practically objectively better than the rest, the usual stale meta stuff which is part of why the game might get boring quickly and runs feel the same. This is a case where quantity and quality is low.TL:DR: Good game with huge issues which might ruin it for some."
