,Recommended,242680,18535869,"Posted: 17 October, 2015",all,Gray Tiamat187,"Original review posted on October 26, 2015:This game is amazing. It is fun and simple, but it is ungodly difficult at the same time. The premise behind the game is simple. You start the game with two characters, these being Crystal and Fish. All characters have two uniquie things. Their passive and their active. Their passive is just that; an ability that will run in the background, influencing your attack patterns and the drops for players. Their active is also known as their right-click ability. Left-click is the basic attack and the default movement is WASD. Just using the two starting characters as an example, I will show how different playstyles can be from character to character.Crystal-Passive: More base health than any other character.-Active: A temporary shield that will reflect multiple bullets and protect you from others.Fish-Passive: Extra ammo recieved-Active: A dodge rollNew review after multiple updates and a very particular mod release:Ah, it's nice to be back to playing this game regularly, but now, there is an extremely different experience of which I must say I enjoy partaking in.Now, if you have looked at the tags, it likely mentioned ""Local Multiplayer"" or ""Local Co-Op,"" but that no longer matters(provided your computer isn't a toaster and your internet isn't an Explorer). There is now a mod(which has been mentioned in the latest news by Vlambeer, so you know it's good) called Nuclear Throne Together, and it does exactly what you think it does; it allows you to play online co-op(or even Vs. with some creative/idiotic friends), albeit at a few costs to the core game.If there was one thing I absolutely loved, it was unlocking all of the characters(and what few B-skins I unlocked before save-editing them in, but that's a different story). The journey felt important, but sadly NTT takes that away by automatically unlocking all characters and B-skins(I know that it does as my idiotic friend hadn't even unlocked Steroids and yet, he was able to play Rouge with her B-skin using the mod).While this certainly does detract from the appeal of the journey, the game is still far from kind and is honestly just downright vicious.Now, since I have basically informed you to get NTT as soon as you start playing the game, I should probably give you some information regarding the rest of the other characters.The first two characters unlocked, Fish and Crystal, I explained in the previous version of this review.The next character, Melting, is unlocked by dying for the first time. He literally looks like a skeleton with melting flesh.Passive-2 health, but recieves an extra Rad(NT's version of Experience) from every enemy(including enemies that don't drop Rads)Active-Explodes all corpses on screen.Next is Eyes, and he's a bit of an interesting character. Firstly, his passive only works on three levels(four, including 4-?), these three(four) being known as the Transition Levels. He's unlocked by reaching the first Transition Level, the Sewers(2-1).Passive-See in the dark(allows him to see the outside boundaries of your FoV in the transition levels)Active-Telekinesis(push bullets away, but pulls enemies and items towards you)Next up is Plant, and boy-oh-boy, do I hate Plant. Plant is unlocked by reaching 3-1(I think), and I only ever unlocked him out of neccessity.Passive-More speed(GOTTSA GO FEST!)Active-Shoot a snare(traps enemies inside of it and acts as a source of light on the Transition Levels).Ah, back to the characters I like, and next up is Yung Venuz(more commonly referred to in game as Y.V.). To unlock Y.V., try to pick up a screwdriver in the desert(1-1 to 1-3) and take it to 3-1(screwdrivers can be found almost anywhere, but it's easiest for them to drop in chests at the very beginning). At 3-1, there will be cars that will explode from too much damage, but there is one car in particular that stands out. Attack that car once with the screwdriver and press your activate button(for me, a mere keyboard user, it is E). You can thank me later.Passive-Higher fire rateActive-Pop Pop(shoot two rounds of ammo for the currently equipped weapon at the cost of a slightly delayed rate of fire)Now, reaching 5-1, we unlock Robot, an interesting(but in my opinion, kind of boring) character to play.Passive-Finds better tech(finds weapons of higher levels than what would drop on any other character)Active-Eat your weapon(consumes the weapon currently equipped as the primary to give ammo for the other weapon).Now, we arrive at 6-1, and here's where things get interesting. Steroids is up next, and he brings a whole slew of power to your arsenal.Passive-Inaccurate(this is okay) and fully automatic fire(no matter what the weapon is)Active-Attacks with the weapon equipped in the off-handYes, that's right. As the load screen will tell you time-and-time again, ""Steroids can duel-weild.""Okay, now we're getting into the spoiler zone, so read at your own risk.Next up is Rebel, a character that can only be unlocked by defeating the Nuclear Throne and ending your run by sitting on it.Passive-Restores half of damage taken when completing level(If she has 2/12(let's say remaining health is X and max health is Y) remaining health when you complete the level, you'll enter the next level with 7, as (Y-X)/2 rounded down in this case would be 5, so (Y-X)/2+X would be the overall equation for her passive.Active-Okay, this one's a bit complex, so bear with me. On her first right click when entering a level, she will lose one HP and a minion will spawn. The minion will last 20 seconds before exploding, but there is a way to extend its lifespan. By right-clicking again, another minion will spawn, and this resets the timer for the first ones life(presumably, it heals them). However, every minion spawned after the first on a single level takes up two HP rather than one(you cannot kill yourself with this ability).Okay, this next character is kind of strange. Horror is unlocked by defeating Horror, who will only spawn when you skip the Rad Canisters on two levels in a row(as such, it is easiest to unlock him on 1-3, but I have accidentally had him spawn in on 4-1 and proceed to end my run).Passive-When choosing a mutation by leveling up, he will have 5 choices(as compared to the usual 4)Active-Ability to shoot accumulated Rads in a concentrated beam as a tertiary weapon(all Rads used in this way will only be regained if they actually hit their target). Also, Rad absorption will be paused when this ability is being used, so keep that in mind).Next is Rogue, and she is definitely the hardest to unlock. First off, when fighting the Nuclear Throne, destroy all of the generators(activated with the Throne's giant laser beam) and then kill the Throne. A portal will open up which leads to the Throne II fight. Beating the Throne II will let you loop, and that's how you unlock Rogue.Passive-All Rad Canisters become ammunition for her Portal Strike, and she's chased by the IDPDActive-Portal StrikeThe last two characters in the mod, Skeleton and Frog, though playable in the original game, they are hidden. Skeleton is only playable by being killed in a Necromancer's circle, and Frog is only playable by saving the Golden Frog Pistol to a character(which is no simple task).SkeletonPassive-4 HP, slowActive-Shoot for no armor at the potential loss of healthFrogPassive-Can't stop, won't stop tryna make the booty drop. Also, he can't be effected by toxic items.Active-Stops moving and begins charging a fart, which will poison anything that enters the toxic cloudSo, yeah, that's about it.I rate this game 9/11, too many cars exploding."
