,Recommended,242680,17192768,"Posted: 23 July, 2015",all,wesnat,"nuclear throne is ♥♥♥♥ing chaos in the best way possible; it's an over-the-top blend of roguelikes, bullet hell, and cover shooters, and it is hard as nails. but in my experience, it's never frustrating or unfair. like spelunky or any other well-made roguelike-inspired game, its challenge and difficulty are outweighed by its addictive ""ok just one more try"" fun.i think nuclear throne's strongest point is its emphasis on individual playstyle. there are no ""bad"" characters, no ""bad"" weapons, no ""bad"" perks to choose when leveling up. everything is carefully designed around the player's own preferences, and whatever unique situations you might find yourself in as you progress. a perk or weapon or character that seems useless or oddly specific will always have special advantages that might not be immediately apparent, and may be critically important later on. vlambeer's careful attention to balance (as shown by their constant updates) has impressively paid off.the artwork is great, the music is great (but kinda loud and overbearing at times), the gameplay is great. my only complaints stem from the currently unfinished menus and options (as of july 2015), but since the game is still in active development, i'm sure they'll be fixed before long. nuclear throne is, in my opinion, a fantastic and clever use of the early access system, and i look forward to seeing where vlambeer takes it from here."
