,Recommended,242680,19687560,"Posted: 13 December, 2015",all,Lu,"Roguelikes have to be my favorite kind of game, and Nuclear Throne happens to be masterfully made to be a nearly perfect roguelike. I've played my fair share of roguelikes, more than what my Steam profile may tell you, and I have to say this is goddamn near the best one. In the aspect of gameplay and intensity, this is certainly the highest ranking roguelike in my opinion, yet I find myself playing more Binding of Isaac sheerly because there's no way to tell what kind of crazy stuff will happen next. Nuclear Throne is more of a straightforward roguelike, there aren't many ""crazy"" things that can happen except for a few secrets that you might accidentally encounter, but it still stands to be intense and engaging in its gameplay. Another thing to mention is that most roguelikes have some kind of ending to the game, yet this does not. Sure, it may have a ""final"" boss, but the game still progresses afterwards and greets you with a few more new bosses on top of stronger incantations of older bosses. The fact that this game never ends, just keeps going and going for as long as you can survive, makes it kind of feel arcade-style, and it makes you want to keep practicing to keep going. So where Nuclear Throne doesn't have as much of a randomness aspect as The Binding of Isaac, it makes up for it by constantly challenging you, no matter how good you are at the game."
