76561198073620047,Not Recommended,242680,22553890,"Posted: 21 April, 2016",all,D-MONEY,"Nuclear Throne. Where to even start. It's simple in design, easy to learn, but impossible to master. I've got a few dozen hours of gameplay as of now, and I've still only managed to beat it once, and not even looping it because I didn't know how when I first got there. It's designed for you to reach the end within about 20 minutes if you play it right, yet after 40+ hours I've only done so once, which goes to show how hard it really is. It's addicting; I can't stop playing even though I must have rage-quit about 150 times already, only to pick it back up after about 20 minutes. There are definitely some flaws in the way the levels and enemies are arranged, allowing for situations where you are just ****ed, but plenty more are the mistakes you make yourself and scream ************!! You might string together profanities that you've never conceived of while playing this game and dying. Yet it keeps calling you back. For that, I'd tell my friends to try it out, but I would not recommend them to buy it if they like winning or have rage problems. It feels like there is something that could be added/fixed to make it more enjoyable than being slaughtered repeatedly. I wish I could make it to looping so I can actually try out the end game, but I've never gotten there and can only imagine there is no magic pixie that will suddenly allow me to reach it more than 2-3 times before I put the game down for good. On a 1-10 scale, I'd rate it a 6.5, simply because it is really fun, but you get so worn down by it's repetitive nature and constant failing (I'm so over the desert starting area). Sure, I get that it is designed to be that way, but it's more rewarding when the difficulty is something you can overcome, rather than being luck-based. Will I keep playing it? Surely, at least until I finally see a loop, but something tells me by the time that happens I'll be done with it for good."
