,Not Recommended,242680,22884870,"Posted: 9 May, 2016",all,█▀█ █▄█ ▀█▀,"Despite me having a (propably unhealthy) amount of hours in this game, I simply can't recommend it, it isn't finished. This game probably won't really be finished. And that's fine. It's a good game, but a problem comes in the fact that it, like I said, isn't finished. There are still situations in which a certain boss (Lil Hunter) can make or break you with no real input on the other player's side. You can go into that fight and have a clear room to fight him in, or a room full of enemies, even multiple elite variants. Glitches, crashing, and general confusing issues are also problematic. I assumed these things would be fixed once it was out of early access, but even after acknowledging it in November, it's May, and it still isn't fixed. As it is right now, I simply cannot reccomend the game. If you want a good shoot-em-up roguelike, you might wanna try Enter the Gungeon. I've only heard good things about it."
,Not Recommended,242680,32802891,Posted: 25 June,all,x2Madda,"While heaps of positive reviews are thrown at this game, I feel it is more because it was a labour of love and a good game to watch other people play than anything to do with the game itself.The game is difficult without actually being hard which I realize requires explination but hard is when something tests your skills and leaves little room for error for example a good bullet hell game and difficult is when factors work against you that you might not have control over which is any game that has RNG with negative odds.The stage layouts are randomized but you can always expect certain events to occour on specific stages, which I like as it lends better to retry attempts unlike FTL where you can get messed up and have zero control over it.In that regard, when compared to its contemporaries Nuclear Throne is a game with good design.However...It is a buggy mess and updates are slow to the point of abandonware with an update being promised in early 2016 that still has not been deployed. Bugs and glitches add a forth dimension to the difficulty as you can die instantly or find yourself in bizaare situations and simply have to give up that run. These are events that are fun to watch such as during a twitch stream but not exactly fun to experience for yourself, infact they are downright antagonistic in a game that leaves little room for error.On that topic, you have 0 recovery frames on hit so you can get cut down immediately if you are prone to moments of panic and some enemies seem to have a ""♥♥♥♥ you"" mode if left alive too long which might not be in your control to do anything about due to low ammo or a bunch of enemies you want to deal with in a controlled fashion so you feel punished for taking a careful approach.No problem, just go gung ho right? well maybe don't! Actually, maybe don't do that. If you run out of ammo then tough. You do not get a melee attack, you will just have 2 guns with empty clips and if no ammo remains then thats too bad kiddo, time to kill yourself.I'm not sure if that was intentional or an oversight and I am not citing it as a negative either way but the game never decides if it wants to be a bullet hell or a roguelike and so sometimes you can go nice, slow and cautious while other times you just end up going balls to the wall as you try to navigate a stage you have done countless times but this time RNG has not blessed you.An arguement can be bad that it is the nature of these games and for a genre I claim to enjoy, I should know that however also par for the course for these games is minor progression. Sure you die over and over but you get some skill or trinket for future runs to make them more palatable however Nuclear Throne doesn't have that, instead you are expected to beat the game in order to hold on to goodies that will help you to, you guessed it, beat the game...Again.This is difficult enough but we have a nasty bug that has become a ""feature"" at this point and its death. Or rather, the effects of death. If you die in multiplayer and are revived, you lose EVERYTHING and that includesyour level up perkswhich I will frankly call a bug since you do not revert back to level one, you simply lose everything and get a middle finger in your face. This makes multiplayer bad, but the bad gets worse because if one person dies and you don't revive them fast enough, you also lose health until you die. You can both make it really far, die, and be stuck with no perks, too far in the game to get anymore and effectively be expected to win on ""skill alone"" which is a kick in the groin but not impossible however if I wanted such a """"""fun"""""" challenge there are actually better bullet hell games out that I could be playing thatdon'thave limited ammo.My issue is that the game fails as a bullet hell because we, the player have limited ammo to retailiate with and it fails as a rogue-lite because the progression requires you to beat the game and thus misses the point and it fails as a co-op game because unless you are both godly at the game, having a partner is just adding an extra you lose condition so all we have left is a game that is fun to watch someone else play so you can enjoy all the action with none of the suffering.Bluntly speaking, this game hasn't aged well and wasn't great when it did launch originally but it was a fresh foray into bullet hell rogue lites which as a whole, hardly has any titles. First impressions are also good so its easy to see why it sold as well as it did. Calling the game bad when it launched would get you beaten up but with the passage of time, better games have come forth and this is just a forgotten relic.If you intend to play solo I can cautiously recommend the game but if you want to play with friends then here is a pro-tip, don't.Join Grumpy reviews for all your gaming needshttp://steamcommunity.com/groups/grumpyreviews"
,Not Recommended,242680,22056219,"Posted: 25 March, 2016",all,TaleLore,"This game is pretty fun. Unfortunately about 1/5 of the time I die due to things that are out of my control, which is frustrating. I was doing extremely well the last time I played, and then the portal to spawn to the next area appeared right next to an exploding car and killed me instantly from full health to nothing.♥♥♥♥♥♥like this happens constantly, so I can't recommend this game even though without all of the ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t it's pretty fun."
76561198027104941,Not Recommended,242680,26305598,"Posted: 29 October, 2016",all,luciasar00,"Nuclear throne makes the curious design decision to put a large amount of content (around 30% or so) at a skill level that is outside what most players are capable of accomplishing under normal circumstances.This game is very, very hard, and unlike hard but inherently progressable games like Dark Souls or Risk of Rain, there is not really anything you can do to get around it - you can't grind or progress your way to victory. At some point, it's likely you'll ""cap out"" your skill level, or get to a point where only hundreds of hours of practice will improve your chances.This capping out point might even be before you ""finish the game"", proper - reaching the Throne is something several of my friends gave up on after 40+ hours of gameplay. ""Looping"" the game is even further out of reach, far beyond anything I was ever able to achieve even as a long time player of difficult shoot-em-ups - you'll notice that many, if not most, of the players discussing loop gameplay on the forums have 100 to 200+ hours of gameplay.This is where content comes in. 5 out of the game's 9 bosses are loop-only. One (and arguably three) of the game's characters are so difficult that they are effectively not practical for most players. Many of the bonus stages are late in the game and require a great deal of skill and luck to unlock. And for many players, runs will end far before they even reach the majority of the stages and enemies in the game. This is a lot of content that if you're not an extremely skilled or dedicated player, you will not (and unlike other similar games, may *never*) get value from.I think it should be obvious from the other reviews that the game's gameplay is pretty on point. There's of course elements of irritation regarding random spawns and powerful enemies, which are also covered better by other reviews. But ultimately, I cannot recommend this game to most players, because a huge proportion of its content is not actually intended for most players. Even if you're able to get decently far, as I did, the sheer amount of content that feels permanently out of your reach can leave a bad taste in your mouth.There's so much that cannot be accessed by a player who is not prepared to sink hundreds of hours into the attempt, and if you're not confident that that's something you'll be willing or able to do, you should be cautious before buying Nuclear Throne."
