76561198006602199,Not Recommended,242680,19687716,"Posted: 13 December, 2015",all,The Operative,"Nuclear Throne is a game that I admire for its execution and its unflinching vision for itself--a punishing rogue-like, action RPG with bullet-hell (or, depending on your play style, cover based shooter) elements. I objectively think Nuclear Throne is a great game and deserves to be played--it's just not a game that I particularly enjoyed, so I'm saying it's a Not Recommend if you think that brutal difficulty and repetition aren't exactly your thing.The best way to show my problem with Nuclear Throne is via numbers: With 21 hours, 32 minutes played, I've unlocked 7/12 characters, unlocked 22% of the game, and gotten as far as the third boss (Lil Hunter), whom I've never beaten. I've died 219 times and never finished a run. This means that I've played the same exact 3 or 4 starting levels almost every single one of those 219 times, killing the same ~3 enemy types per level. Sometimes I get farther, but I always have to play through those levels.Even with the well-designed, different characters, this repetition starts wearing thin. I'm really sick of these opening levels. This problem is exacerbated by how easily death ends a run. A slight misestimation of a bullet's trajectory, an accidental bump into a hidden enemy, poking your head out at exactly the wrong moment--one misstep and suddenly you're back at 1-1.The action is fast-paced and frenetic, and, when it hits a rhythm, Nuclear Throng can be fun. But, even as someone who enjoys really difficult games and loves rogue-likes (FTL is one of my favorite and most played games of all time), Nuclear Throne isn't for me--something I realized somewhere between my first aggravating death and my 219th."
