76561198088138921,Recommended,242680,18535373,"Posted: 17 October, 2015",all,ArsonsAra,"Nuclear Throne. I wrote a review about this game a long, long time ago. And now it's early-access state is coming to a close, and the finished product is within reach. Amazing, isn't it? To think this game was at first a simple Game Jam project, and has turned into one of Steam's finest games. Certianly something, huh? Well, let's look at the game in it's somewhat complete state and see what it has to offer.The game is a bullet hell, in every sense of the word. Nuclear Throne is a game in which you play as mutants that were created or survivied the end of the world. Wether they be A Fish, A walking chunk of crystal, a person who's flesh is constantly melting, or a Gun God, you have a variety of characters. And even two new ones! While i've yet to unlock them it's glad to see that Vlambeer made new characters. However, I feel they're a tad hard to unlock seeing as I haven't yet, but hey I can't wait to do so. And maybe we can get even more new characters in the future, but that's wishful thinking on my part. As for the gameplay it's hectic as hell. You start off with only a revolver, your wits, and any secondary powers given depending on the character you choose. As you collect Rads, which is this game's equivalent of EXP, You level up and gain Mutations. Which can give you more health, deal more damage, and other perks. You're given a selection of four mutations (or five if you're playing as one of the unlockable characters) and they're all good. Sooner or later you'll get into the groove of the game and find your favorite characters, weapons and mutations. And your goal, Reach the Nuclear Throne. For now, let's touch on the story. It's amazing. The story is sprinkled bit by bit in every part of the game, and it's certainly interesting and it's hard not to get invested.Nuclear Throne is the perfect game for when you want a challenge, but one that's fair. Nuclear Throne is like that one relative in your family that can reward you with a lot of cool stuff, but only if you work hard. You want to kill the Nuclear Throne? You have to earn it. You want your favorite mutation? Sorry, you'll have to deal with what I have now, and work hard with what you have. It's hard, but it doesn't treat you like a baby. The game is very balanced and while difficult, is not impossible. And you don't need to have the reflexes of a god to be good at the game. You just need to keep playing and improve. Which is extreemly rewarding. Nothing is more satisfying than geting farther in the game than you ever have, and nothing will ever compare to beating the Nuclear Throne for the first time ever.The only two problems I have aren't game ruining. One small, and one a tad big. There is one NPC in the game that I feel is wholy unpredictable, and can be very hard to deal with because of that. Alligators. I feel like I can never tell when they're going to fire and they're range is kind of crazy. Sometimes they do nothing. Other times they go in guns blazing and it feels unfair. I can never predict what they're going to do. And unlike the Assasins, that while hard to deal with, you can learn they're patterns, the Alligators feel like they do whatever they want. And another thing about the game, is the reason it's so good. But is also it's worst enemy. Every level is randomly generated, besides a few exceptions. Which can make the game replayable for years to come. But can also make it unfair. Some stages can kill you simply because they overwhelm you in ways you can't fight back. Which is hard to deal with, it's hard to make a game random and fair and the same time. It's really hard, but sometimes I get a really good run going, only to have it stop because there are seven Snipers hiding behind Big Dog.But other than that, I love this game. It's a wonderful time sink, and almost every run feels adrenaline pumping.And Vlambeer, if you're reading this. Thank you. Thank you so much for making such an amazing game. I love the gamplay and I love the story. I honestly feel like the story is amazing and I love finding more about it. I feel like it'd be a dream if I got to interview any of you and ask questions, or hell even work on the game's story with you guys! But that's just wishfull thinking, and enteirly up to you guys. But I doubt it'll ever happen. But either way, thanks for making such an amazing, and timeless game. And I can't wait to see what you guys have in store next."
