76561198108408872,Recommended,242680,18650517,"Posted: 23 October, 2015",all,dejp1993,"I love arcade games, and have other good ones on Steam like Broforce, Iron Fisticle and Gauntlet Slayer Edition.   This one is tied with Broforce as my favorite Steam game."
,Recommended,242680,13921512,"Posted: 10 January, 2015",all,Regulith,"I know what you're thinking, because I thought it too. 13 bucks for some beta indie game? No sale in sight? Doesn't seem very reasonable. And for some people that might be true! But I really do think this game can be worth the money if you're into what it's offering, and it's offering a lot more than most.In its current state, Nuclear Throne is a VERY difficult roguelite. BRUTALLY difficult. It ain't no Binding of Isaac, no offense of course to Mr. McMillen. You play as one of twelve characters, each with their own unique attributes and special abilities, attempting to reach the Nuclear Throne and rule the post-apocalyptic wasteland. Only a handful of these characters are unlocked from the start, with the rest requiring reaching a certain point or doing certain tasks.Throughout your journey in this twin-stick shooter, you will encounter an array of devious enemies, each one eliciting a ""HE CAN DO THAT?"" as you stare in awe at your death screen. Plenty of weapons are scattered about the wasteland to help dispatch those baddies, ranging from Laser Pistols to Flame Shotguns to Gattling Bazookas. Weapons dip into different ammunition reserves depending on the type, keeping you on your toes and sometimes requiring you to ditch one for another if your aim isn't up to par. You can even increase your chances of finding better weaponry by leaving a level with weapon chests unopened.Your radiation will build as you defeat enemies and break open canisters, occasionally allowing you to mutate upon completing a level, giving you upgrades such as greater melee distance or vampiric kills. The special Throne Butt mutation varies in effect depending on character, enhancing their special ability. There's no time limit, so you can take your time picking off enemies if you so choose, but you'll often find yourself desperately scrambling for bullets or medkits amidst a mass of enemies and getting obliterated.Nuclear Throne has a daily run feature, pitting every player against each other on the same exact run; a similar weekly run feature that runs from Friday to Sunday and requires you to play with a set loudout with as many tries as you want; the game receives updates every weekend, and they even regularly stream game development to boot. Things are still being tweaked, but the game is very close to being complete and most of the features are fully implemented. Achievement hunters will be disappointed to find that achievements are not yet implemented despite appearing on Steam.The price may seem high to some people considering the circumstances, but I think playing a part on the development of this game is more than worth it, especially in a world where the average indie Kickstarter demands an extra $10-20 for beta access. Here's to the future of Nuclear Throne!FLÄSHYN!"
