,Recommended,242680,23626559,"Posted: 17 June, 2016",all,Special Meme Fresh,"Nuclear Throne is a very hard game, whether it's fair or not is up for debate however. It is way to easy to have a cheap death, though the game is designed around that, and pretty well at that. It's weird how I can like a game that is DESIGNED around one of its biggest flaws, a really risky move on Vlambeer that it's hard to say whether it paid off or not. The amount of things in the game that can kill you instantly are astounding. I am not certain, but I believe there is an instakill hazard of some kind on nearly every floor, or at least a very difficult to expect attack that will most likely hurt you for a bit. Its hard to get invested in a run because of this, but it is still really easy to get invested in the game because of how quickly you can start a new run. I personally believe this worked very well, and to help get my point across, I am going to compare and contrast it to the game I have to absolute most time on, The Binding of Isaac: Rebirth.In nuclear throne it is really easy to take damage, and only a little bit easier to recover relative to BOI. In BOI, the most damage you can take from a single enemy attack, is one full heart, and you can have 12 hearts, AND you get a prolonged period of invulnerability after each hit you take. However, the average complete run for BOI takes around 30 minutes, more or less depending on your luck, the average run for NT however is around half that, less depending on your playstyle. The biggest factor on the time of a run for BOI is luck, while playstyle is the biggest factor for NT. I would say either makes me feel better to complete, as BOI can be so satisfying to watch the perfect build come together, while nuclear throne can be so satisfying after every boss you beat, knowing you earned the victory. I wouldn't say either is better that the other in that sense, so I will still come back to each at some point, so its nice that they both work differently.As I said, in NT it is really easy to take damage, and sometimes, the damage you take is not deserved. The biggest example being the cars, especially in the scrapyard. Where after defeating every enemy in a level, something that can happen really quick if you aren't paying attention, if you are near a car and the portal taking you to the next level appears, the car explodes and you likely end up dying. Even worse is it feels that the gold rimmed carthat is used to get to Y.V's mansion to receive a golden weaponseems to explode sometimes at random, making unlocking Y.V's B skin that much harder to get. The closest thing in BOI to this is probably curse of the blind, or curse of the maze, where you can accidently pick up a run-ending item, or accidently get shoved into a room you weren't expecting to and being damaged. Worse being the former, however it is the only time a run can be ruined, and even then there is a chance of recovery.In short, this game is more skill based than Binding of Isaac, however it seemed to try way too hard to be dfficult to the point where it risked losing some of its fun factor. Its not fun to die out of no fault of your own, but its so easy to start a new run, that it 'almost' doesn't even matter. Overall I reccomend it, probably not as much as Binding of Isaac in the end, but I still enjoyed it despite any of its flaws, no matter how much the game insists on shoving them in my face.Overall Score 7.75/10"
,Recommended,242680,23627416,"Posted: 17 June, 2016",all,Gig,"A great ""Coffee Break"" type game that can also be played for long extended periods. I find myself playing this while just needing to pass a couple minutes or waiting on something else, and other times I'll sit down and just try to loop for as long as possible, or give as many different runs as I can. Very little progress is tracked between runs, but that's okay - and also a bit less stressful, in a way.The game does not hold your hand nor pull any punches - you will die on the first screen multiple times, you will die numerous times before even getting halfway, you will die many times before reaching the throne.But your perserverance will be WELL rewarded. Death is a great teaching tool in this game, and being able to wade through the countless losses will not only net you cooler/more badass/more interesting guns as you get farther along in a run, but as you get better and better you'll slowly find yourself becoming a god of the game capable of badass maneuvers you never thought possible before. Though that first screen will still kill you from time to time, getting into just the right positions will make you into a God of Mayhem.This game sat on my wishlist for a while because, though I was interested, I was hesitant about buying the game at full price and wanted to wait for a sale. I'd played Vlambeers games before, and while I liked them, didn't see much special in what they were making. I eventually caved and bought it at full on a whim one day, and have not regretted it whatsoever. The money was well spent, and if this game were to never go on sale it'd still be a steal.I wish other AAA non-roguelite games had this depth of weaponry, character development, and gameplay. This honestly is a rare gem of a game, and they're still working on it.If you're still worried about not wanting to play because you're not ""good enough"", trust me - this game will make you good enough whether you want to be or not.My only wish is that they had a demo. There'ssomuch that can't be ""got"" about this game through words and video alone."
