,Recommended,242680,11901761,"Posted: 28 August, 2014",all,Atticus Zed,"Note: This is an Early Access Review, but this game is just about completed anyway. Everything is fully functional, and the devs are just fixing up some aesthetic discrepancies and adding a few more weapons, and it looks like it'll be all finished up. So don't let the Early Access scare you off of this one.Really great game. I can hardly tell this is still an Early Access (although I have to say that I've noticed flashes of giant cyan squares here and there that suggest an unfinished sprite set...)The gameplay is super smooth and fluid, and the fact that there is no notable cooldown to any of your character's skills only boosts the fluidity and fast-paced gameplay even further. $13 is a little rich for my blood, but that's only because I haven't bought anything on Steam for over $10 in months, and I've been a little spoiled. It was definitely worth the price tag.While all the gameplay mechanics are brilliantly crafted, though, I DO have a couple gripes about this game. FIrst off, being a procedural death game, you can expect to die. A lot. So my largest problem is the overall predictability of the game. The general scenery and progression of the game does no changing from playthrough to playthrough, so it can get kind of dull after a while.While on the subject of dying, a lot of the deaths you'll experience can feel really cheap. 8 health LOOKS like a lot, but once you get shot by a grunt and notice it takes away 3 points of health, all sense of survivability will quickly be lost on you -  meaning it can be pretty hard to gauge what will kill you if you're hit by it and what won't. Even at 12 health with the Rhino Skin enhancement, it still seems like a lot of things can just instant kill you. I can't even count how many times I've died in the Wasteland because an offscreen assassin came up and chopped me in half. If it wasn't that, it was an explosive death, often because I slightly misjudged the distance between me and a Sniper.Even so, I've never really gotten mad with the game. Annoyed, yes, but never genuinely mad."
