76561198149037095,Recommended,242680,21761912,"Posted: 11 March, 2016",all,Vogelmeister,"It's all fun and games at first: you fire a few shots from your revolver, kill some lumpy desert mummies, dodge a bullet here and there, probably reach the area boss and feel generally good about yourself. Then you die and start over. And over. And over. Because that's what it's all about - dedication and persistence. So by the time you reach the third area, you'll probably have unlocked some characters and played around with quite a few weapons (occasionally blowing yourself up in the process). You feel more confident now. Familiar with your surroundings. You keep pressing on, fine-tuning your strategies and eventually approaching the ultimate goal, the titular Nuclear Throne, one step at a time.And it's great. The game has very solid combat mechanics, the weapons all feel ""just right"". It's enjoyable, it's very challenging, and the constant flow of adrenaline it provides is enough to keep you going for a long time.Until eventually you hit a wall and stop.All of a sudden this jolly old rogue-fest turns into a groundhog day simulator. You realize that the levels are always the same. The layouts are randomly generated, of course, but their contents are quite similar every time. Things stop unlocking sooner or later, too, mostly because you're just not good enough. And you could keep practicing and honing your skills, of course, but at that point constantly repeating the easier areas becomes a torturous grind. There's just not enough variety in items and abilities to work for. The challenge is still there, but the reward is gone, and you probably didn't even notice, did you?I suppose there are two ways to go from there. You either carry on out of dedication or spite for over 900 hours (there are leaderboards and everytrhing), or you simply stop playing, relish what good moments you had with the game and reflect on just how much you value your time.Try this game either way. It's good."
