76561197976822079,Recommended,242680,22048155,"Posted: 25 March, 2016",all,Appetite4Deduction,"It's always interesting when people refer to ""roguelike"" and ""shooter"" in the same sentence.  Nuclear Throne is one of those games that pulls it off masterfully.In terms of ""roguelike,"" it has perma-death, random level layout generation, linear stage progression, and item pickups and upgrades galore.  In terms of ""shooter,"" well, it has a great combination of strategy and all-out mayhem.And it's hard.  Probably you figured as much.  You have a tiny life bar and no temporary invincibility after you are hit.  You will die, and die, and die...and somehow it never stops being super fun.The only negative that I see with this game is that the graphics are thrown together.  They aren't bad, but there is a cheapness to them that can wear on your eyes if you aren't used to the low-resolution pixelation.  The default screen shake setting is also game-breaking, so I highly recommend reducing it.Cheap graphics are complemented by some of the cleverest sound design I've heard in a video game in a long time.  There are tons of sound effects, an awesome musical score, and a surprisingly rich array of voice acting, even if the voices are all silly and incomprehensible alien/monster tongues.The game is very rewarding to players who keep trying to get better--there are secrets to find, weapon combinations to exploit, and special character abilities and upgrades to unlock.  Pay whatever price Vlambeer demands--it will be worth your while."
