76561198103310289,Recommended,242680,25286270,"Posted: 1 September, 2016",all,FaultLine,"Personally, I enjoyed this game. The graphics carry a pixely charm, the video settings (most notably screenshake) make the game feel alive, and each character gives a different flavor and playstyle to a run.But among the genre, this isn't for every roguelike connesour.It's punishing. It's brutal. It takes a long time to get the hang of it, and only after >80 hours will you get that joy of geting over that hump, that point where the levels of frustration the game brings diminishes (as with most roguelikes). You need to know this game inside and out to have a good run, and that may be seen as too much of a time investment for some, and the variety minimizes the deviation from run to run, making it a little more samey than other roguelikes.In short, the skill celling is this genre's equivalent to Civ's, with a replay value that varies wildly from person to person. 7/10"
