76561198120961964,Recommended,242680,26479130,"Posted: 7 November, 2016",all,Surely You Chespin,"I can't recommend this game strongly enough. It's just good. I'm not even that good at it, but I find myself coming back to it more and more.First off, the art style. It's beautiful, with what I want to say is a bit of an arcade feel? The character designs, from players to enemies to bosses to... vans and radioactive chairs? just looks good. Not overly complex, not too simple. A nice balance. There's other visual effects such as sccreen shake to make you almost feel the explosions and guns firing.Next, the soundtrack. Gorgeous. Post-apocalyptic. The game makes nice use of its own leitmotif, in a similar vein to how Undertale uses its own, though the soundtracks have a much different feel to them for sure. Ambience is used to excellent effect, with the best example probably being the Crystal Caves. Those spidery scamper sounds will send shivers up your spine. Annoying alliteration aside, all the other audio is also amazing. Sound effects are great. You swing a melee weapon and it sounds, as one Nuclear Throne YouTuber would put it: crunchy. You shoot a Revolver and it really sounds and even feels like you're shooting a gun.Finally, gameplay. An excellently paced rogue-like top-down bullet-hell shooter. Areas follow an interesting floor pattern of 3,1,3,1 and so on. Areas with 3 floors hold a boss at the end, while areas with one serve as a vastly different transition area, with darker lighting to boot. The leveling system involves collecting ""rads"" which function like EXP, though they disappear if you don't collect them in time. With enough rads, you can mutate, granting buffs like revenge damage, extra ammo storage, reduced enemy health, and even... bolts that somehow seek out enemies? Speaking of bolts, there are several weapon types, each with their own ammo class and sub-types, such as Bolts/Seekers/Splinters, Shells/Slugs, Bullets/Bouncers, and others. I don't know exactly how many weapons are in the game, but there are plenty, and finding the ones that work best for you is part of the fun. There are also plenty of secrets in the game as well... try taking a Screwdriver to the gold car in 3-1 some time.There are also some great mods for the game. The two that stand out the most are Ultra Mod and Together. Ultra adds seeral new weapons, areas, characters, enemies, and bosses. Probably about double of everything. Unfortunately, it was started before the Throne was actually added, so that feature is missing, but it's still an excellent mod. Together is fully based around the current version and through some miracle adds online support to a game that currently has none, as well as altering some of the mechanics introduced for the Local Co-op already included in the game. In fact, I'd recommend getting this mod off the bat, since it's literally just Nuclear Throne... Together.Seriously. It's just a good freakin game. Buy it. Support the devs in their quest to work on the PS3 port, which they've unfortunately been struggling with since it's literally the first Game Maker game ported to the system, which leads to all sorts of problems that aren't necessarily the Vlambeer devs' faults. Help them bring this amazing game to a wider audience."
