76561197970552278,Recommended,242680,20098631,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,Sorceror Bob,"In each game of Nuclear Throne, you start as one of a handful of characters, each with their own strengths, and at times, weaknesses.  That's it.  You're thrown straight into the action, with only the barest whisper of an over-arching narrative.  Upon your first death, you're told 'you did not reach the Nuclear Throne', thus fixing the games objective squarely in your sights.Perhaps I am getting old and slow, but I find Nuclear Throne fiendishly challenging.  As with most rogue-likes, progression is determined by a combination of luck, and of pure skill.  Your character levels up by collecting rads from fallen enemies.  Collect enough, and you can select one of a handful of mutations when you finish the level.  I find that luck of the draw at the earlier levels can be key, and collecting enough rads in the first stages to level up a couple of times can make future runs much easier.To assist in your quest, the game features a diverse arsenal of weapons, also dropped at random.  These range from melee to ranged, and players will come up with their own preferences.One thing the game does really well, is synergise the various systems.  On one of my most successful run throughs, I played as the Robot (can eat weapons for health and ammo, and has a chance to collect higher tier weapons).  Early on, I picked up the steady aim and shotgun shoulders mutations.  When combined with a double barrelled shotgun, a single blast would see a tight grouping of projectiles bounce off walls almost endlessly.  On constrained levels with few open areas, it was a very effective, and safe way of clearing levels.If that is a moment where everything has come together, I can cite many more where bad luck has lead to an unfortunate death.  One point of frustration involves the portals that are created when you clear a level.  These burst open, destroying all items around them, whilst pulling you toward them.  One set of levels feature cars that explode, and it seems to be my like that the portals open right on top of them, dragging my character to a swift explodey death.But, even with these moments, I'm still having loads of fun.  The controls are sharp with a keyboard and mouse combo (haven't tried with a controller), and death is but a momentary setback.  Games run so quick, that it's possible to recover lost progress in only a few minutes.Nuclear Throne is the perfect game to play when you only have a sneaky fifteen minutes or so, but also a great choice for longer plays.  Also a great option for mates, as the short game times work well in a 'life by life' arrangement."
