76561198132792574,Recommended,242680,24324398,"Posted: 14 July, 2016",all,armoredrobot,"I've played two Vlambeer games now -the other one being Super Crate Box- and I've noticed a common theme: insertion of the mainstays of an old-school FPS (lots of guns, lots of enemies, cathartic gameplay, basically whatever Serious Sam does) into other, older genres to see what happens. With Super Crate Box, the genre in question is an 8-bit platformer, along the lines of the original Donkey Kong. In Nuclear Throne, it's a top-down bullet hell shooter (with RPG elements), which is a wonderful choice for combination with an old-school FPS. However, doing so means that the game has to take away the FPS ability to tank absurd amounts of damage, which is where the roguelite elements come in.Nuclear Throne's main issue for me is that, upon death, no matter how far you are, you're sent all the way back to the start. I'd expect nothing less from a roguelite ('roguelite' for me meaning it has randomization and permadeath), and this wouldn't be a problem but for the fact that the first levels will soon become VERY familiar, because they only vary so much, and contain the least interesting weapons and enemies. I can see why the decision was made; if you could save, you could finish the game in about 20 minutes, and being a roguelite means that the devs don't have to balance the massive amount of weapons and enemies, both of which are spawned randomly and vary widely in terms of power. Still, managing to kill Li'l Hunter (the game's other issue) and then being blown up by a random car because you weren't being careful with your explosives, only to be sent ALL the way back to the start, can be...disheartening, to say the least.That's essentially my only problem with the game, though, and judging by the fact that I've put 206 hours into it at time of writing, it doesn't stop me from playing. I love Nuclear Throne. I love its adrenaline-soaked gameplay, I love its crushing difficulty, I love its increasingly bizarre arsenal, I love its variety, and I could talk about it for hours.I won't here, though, because these reviews are disjointed and rambling enough already. Suffice it to say that I like to play Robot, my favorite mutation is Gamma Guts, and my favorite weapons are the Eraser and the Seeker Shotgun.Anyway, yes. I love Nuclear Throne, and I recommend it to everyone. It's my favorite roguelite of all time. Sorry, FTL. To quote Saints Row 2, you lost to the best."
76561198285075314,Recommended,242680,24359714,"Posted: 16 July, 2016",all,Trash Typhoon,"This game is perfect, i have spend hundreds of hours playing this. This game has so much to offer and is worth all the money you've spent on it."
