,Recommended,242680,20243917,"Posted: 2 January, 2016",all,Jergling,"Initially, I was miffed that this game was 30fps and in what might be the ugliest, most cluttered fake-isometric perspective I've ever seen. I hated it, but I was also playing it on a TV with a gamepad. This was a bad idea.Nuclear Throne is a keyboard and mouse game, make no mistake. The controller-required co-op mode is a token add-on that has more downsides than benefits. Play this game on a fast monitor and contrast turned up, and you'll have fewer problems.The light at the end of the tunnel is that Nuclear Throne is basically a procedural, single-life version of Hotline Miami. Everything is very fast, there are guns everywhere, and there's a ton of content. Nuclear Throne is about variety, difficulty, and how fast it is to get into a new game. That's where Vlambeer got it right and others (like Isaac) didn't. Death is permanent, but restarting is so fast and easy that you hardly feel it. Vlambeer had mastered the art of permadeath long before roguelikes took off, and I do feel like this is a glorious return to the Super Crate Box days, despite running at half the framerate."
