,Recommended,242680,21844970,"Posted: 14 March, 2016",all,Modus Pwnens,"A very fun game when it goes reasonably well, but the randomization can get frustrating even by roguelike standards.Pros:The guns feel good, the enemy design feels good, the mutations can cause you to adapt to different playstyles you might otherwise overlook, the character powers are interesting (with one or two exceptions that are not very fun or interesting), and the bosses are mostly well-designed.Cons:The enemy placement has soul-crushingly bad randomization, even for a roguelike.Once you're moderately competent at the game, your success is largely a function of rolling dice a dozen times hoping you never roll a 1. The problem is that the randomization makes the variance in difficulty too high. You'll relatively quickly get to the point where you can reliably beat a given level almost every time, but then 5% of the time that level will spawn you in the center of five rapid-fire enemies who immediately start shooting, three snipers, and a monster who spews AoE flames. Is it possible to survive those spawns? Sure - you can go on Youtube and watch people do it. But the discrepancy in skill required to be able to reliably beat the level in almost all cases and to be able to reliably beat the level when you get unlucky is just too massive.It creates a very ugly long-term difficulty curve where there's a long period of time that you're good enough at the game to make it to the end except when you get unlucky - and every run for hours and hours will be predicated on whether you get unlucky or not.The other big con is the third boss. The internet is full of complaints about this boss. Watch Youtube videos of the best players and the commentary will frequently suggest that they're still afraid of this boss. And that same commentary will reveal the problem: it isn't that the boss is too hard, it's that the boss showcases the randomization problems more acutely than anything else in the game. You can end up spawned in a position where it's functionally impossible to survive. You can be spawned in the open with thirty enemies and not nearly enough time to clear them out before the boss spawns. You can be spawned in corridor so long and narrow that it's impossible to avoid his bouncing attacks.It's a shame because that boss is otherwise the best boss in the game. The attack patterns are fun, if you're in a decent spawn he's hard but manageable, and you can quickly come up with clear strategies to deal with him. But the decision to have you fight him in a totally random map with random enemy placements turns a fun boss into a source of frustration.Finally, the boss also has an incredibly stupid gimmick - when you get to him, he'll start powering up, then an instant-death beam will cut straight down the middle of the screen with no warning (and there's no aperature or any reason to expect something to come out there).It's a cheap shot that all but guarantees new players will die once. It feels like the developers added it to play into the idea that the game is hard, but it isn't hard - it's just a cheap shot that will leave you angry that you finally got to the last boss and the developers played what amounts to a practical joke on you and told you to go do it again. It feels incredibly out of place compared to the rest of the enemy design in the game and the game is worse for it.Overall:All in all, a very fun game hampered mostly by its questionable enemy and level randomization. If you're prone to feeling frustration when you feel like there's nothing you could have done to prevent your death (and having to start all over), I'd give this one a pass. If you think you can put up with it, I'd say the gameplay just barely makes up for it, edging it ever so slightly into recommented territory."
,Recommended,242680,21810190,"Posted: 13 March, 2016",all,A Beer,"Please help me.  I can't stop playing this.I also can't seem to beat it, because holy christ on a popsicle stick it is hard.  Like up the butt hard."
76561198156544884,Recommended,242680,21923333,"Posted: 19 March, 2016",all,Chistletof,Do you like guns?Do you like a challenge?Do you like a lot of guns?Do you like chaos?Then this game is for you.(Note: Barrels explode. Don't wack them with a melee on your first playthrough)
,Recommended,242680,21239364,"Posted: 15 February, 2016",all,Jatrick,"This game is hard, but making these cookies aren't.2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour1 teaspoon baking soda1 1/2 teaspoons cornstarch1/2 teaspoon salt3/4 cup packed brown sugar1/2 cup granulated sugar3/4 cup unsalted butter, melted1 egg + 1 egg yolk1 tablespoon vanilla extract1 cup milk chocolate chipsIn a large bowl, sift together 2 and 1/4 cups all-purpose flour, 1 teaspoon baking soda, 1 and 1/2 teaspoons cornstarch, and 1/2 teaspoon salt.In another bowl, whisk together 3/4 cup packed brown sugar, 1/2 cup granulated sugar and 3/4 cup melted butter. Whisk until the sugars have dissolved into the butter. Add in the egg and egg yolk, and whisk. Then add in 1 tablespoon vanilla extract.Pour the wet ingredients into the dry. Use a large wooden spoon to combine the ingredients together. Fold in 1 cup milk chocolate chips.Place the dough in a large bowl, cover, and chill in the refrigerator for at least 3 hours. I chilled my dough overnight.When you’re ready to bake the cookies, pre-heat your oven to 325 degrees. Pull the dough out of the fridge and let it sit for about 10 minutes.Line baking sheets with parchment paper. The dough is going to be hard, and firm, and a little bit difficult to work with.Use 3 tablespoons of dough for each cookie. Use your hands to form the dough into balls. Press a few additional chocolate chips onto the top of the dough ball.Give each cookie a good amount of space on the baking sheets. I was able to fit about 6 cookies per cookie sheet.Bake for 11-12 minutes. The cookies are going to appear under-baked. This is what you want!Allow the cookies to cool for about 10 minutes before transferring them to wire cooling racks to finish cooling.These will stay fresh for about 7 days. You will get about 16 cookies from this batch. If you’d like to make them a bit smaller, use 2 tablespoons of dough and bake for 10 minutes."
