76561198060219701,Recommended,242680,28296121,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,lostcraft,"Nuclear Throne: A top-down ""roguelike-light"" shooter that combines the usual trappings (permadeath, randomized levels, character upgrades, loot tables) with crisp retro pixel art, frantic shooting, and teeth-gnashing difficulty. Highly recommended, and here's why.The world has changed. Once there were humans here, and trees, and things were good. Now there's only the wasteland, the ruins of human civilization, and an awful lot of monsters and mutants. And somewhere, there is the Nuclear Throne. Sitting on it, legend tells, can make things right, and a bunch of determined mutans set out to rest their very backside on that very legendary throne.Pick a mutant, each with their own unique passive and active ability, enter the wasteland with nothing but a small pistol and some ammo, and say hello to a brutal dry wasteland. You move your potential hero with the WASD keys, aim and shoot with the mouse, and... by now you're already dead. It happens. It will happen a lot. In Nuclear Throne, every single pixel is deadly and wants to see you dead. Getting used to the controls won't take you too long, though, and you *are* always in full control, everything's nice and smooth and precise. As you get a hang of things, you'll pick up better weapons, more ammo, and radiation: That's the stuff that allows you to level up and get new abilities... by mutating some more. Want more speed? Grow some extra legs. Weapons take too long to reload? Get yourself some trigger fingers. Love the shotgun? Get Shotgun Shoulders and see those bullets spray. Like weapons, the mutations you get to pick are randomized, adding some unpredictable element to each run. Across seven stages, things get hairier and more dangerous, always introducing some new enemy, and you also have to make your way past bosses that add some extra challenge.Nuclear Throne is an unforgiving game. From the get-go, you are outnumbered and underpowered, barely able to take more than three direct hits from a normal enemy before your run's over. Better weapons and a good set of mutations can only get you so far: Your skill at dodging, reading a fight, and reacting within a second to yet another spray of bullets is what will get you further into the game. NC makes it easy to jump back into the fray: One click and you're there again, in the wasteland, and maybe this time...With a good dozen of different mutants to unlock, with a nice range of little secrets to find, and with a raw, charming presentation, Nuclear Throne is a skill game that will tax your patience but will always see you coming back. There's a lot of satisfying gunplay, there's hilariously overpowered weapons, there's plenty of Yet Another Stoopid Death moments. This game has personality and attitude. It has staying power.For those who care about this sort of thing, NC was made in Game Maker, and it showcases how to make a good solid game in that toolkit. There are some design decisions that tend to rub people the wrong way, most norably the lack of widescreen support and a hardcoded 30FPS lock, but these decisions are part of the very design- personally I never found any of them being a ""bad thing"". I'm usually far too busy exploding corpses with my MIND and clubbing monsters with a WRENCH. Through WALLS.It also has a pretty darn good soundtrack!"
76561197987446125,Recommended,242680,28302438,"Posted: 10 December, 2016",all,supersamuraiseung,"Fantastic hi-octane arcade-skill twin-stick shooter throwback. Bugs aside (which has only really ruined a single run for me in 80+ hours of play so far but something to be wary of), the polish of the package as a whole is amazing. The sound design in particular just makes the game a joy to play. What NT does the best over its competitors is the sound effects of each one of the guns - it just makes them so satisfying to use (none of that weakass pew-pew ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t)"
