76561198120435099,Recommended,242680,29659130,Posted: 2 February,all,Autismo,"Nuclear Throne is a over-the-top top-down roguelike bullet hell shooter. And I still get confused by music genres. Nice.Nuclear Throne is a very action packed, almost 90s-style game with explosions every picosecond and a constant tinnitus of gunfire in your ear, not unlike DOOM. A ""testosteronefest,"" if you will. Nuclear Throne pulls this off very well with a great blend of fast-paced gameplay, gritty retro aesthetics, satisfying gun sounds, and an enormous arsenal of ridiculous and barbaric weapons.The game features a cast of interesting characters to fit different play styles. If you want to be super aggressive, you can play as ""Steroids,""  who can wield 2 weapons at once and go full-auto with any weapons. If you're a ♥♥♥♥♥ like myself, you can play crystal, who can surround themself in a crystal shield and ignore any outside dangers. Kind of like how I deal with responsibilities in real life, only it actually works.Being a roguelike, there is a lot of RNG in Nuclear Throne. Unlike some games, though, RNG doesn't really dictate how well your run goes, apart from an awkward spawn location every once in a while. Basically, if you want to get it up the♥♥♥♥♥from RNGsus, there's a game called Binding Of Isaac which you would probably enjoy.Though RNG isn't going to kill your dreams, it's not going to hand them over to you, either. There are no absurdly game-breaking combos that will basically win the game for you.That brings me to my next point: the difficulty. This game doesn't mess around. You usually take between 3-5 damage per shot, and health pickups only restore 2. Since you only have a max health of 8, there's little room for error.To conclude, Nuclear Throne is a very solid game if you want a repeatable and exciting roguelike."
