,Not Recommended,242680,7534027,"Posted: 31 October, 2013",all,Barcode x_x,"The Wasteland calls to youA beautiful rain of corpsesIs MeltingEDIT: I have just been informed (on good authority) that if you sit upon the Throne, you 'splosion. 11/10EDITEDIT: After 400 hours I can actually make an informed review: don't buy this game, the presentation (art, music, etc) are all top-notch but the actual gameplay isn't respectful of the players time. It'll take different people a varying amount of time to realise this and for me, far too much time passed before I began to clue onto it.It's pretty divisive, calling a game frustrating. Some people take that as a positive, something to plough through and feel accomplishment after 'beating' the game, despite itself. Some take it to be a negative, some fault of the game that sucks the fun out. Others still claim that frustration is born from a lack of skill or talent at the game, and if you practise or 'get good' at the game, then fun awaits you.Ultimately, Nuclear Throne hoodwinks the player by making you think that a death was the result of your actions leading up to or during your death, when really it's inevitably tied to some rather strange design decisions during early access that persisted into the now abandoned released state. Good games are ultimately an interesting series of choices, and Nuclear Throne succeeds for as long as it is able to convince you that it has interesting choices for you, the player. The moment you realise that there is only one way to successfully play the game, and that all apparent 'choices' are really just gotchas, then you're essentially done with Nuclear Throne.A good example would be the red weapon chests. If you open one, you find a random weapon of your current levels tier or any tier below that. Yes, this means you can find Level 1 weapons in a late game / post-loop weapon chest. However, if you don't open a weapon chest for anywhere between 1-3 levels, the game will spawn a big weapon chest and drop 3 weapons. Because of the way the weapon tier drops work, this ultimately gives you a greater chance to find a good gun.So, the intention here was - do you want a weaponnow, or hold out and hope for something greater later. It looks like an interesting choice, which is what games like this boil down to. Except, the right choice is to ALWAYS wait for a big chest. No exceptions. And it took me a paragraph to briefly outline why that is, and I still don't think it is very intuitive. The whole game is like this. Every single apparent choice actually has an 'optimal' solution.This is a problem, because the game is very unforgiving in it's difficulty. Normally, I'm a proponent of this, except when you can't meaningfully change how you're going to approach the game, it kills replayability. Ammo/HP drops are another example of unintuitive play - they're tied to your ammo count. So, holding a melee weapon will change if you see HP packs or not. Or, having a full clip in your backup weapon means you'll see less health...Again, this is supposed to encourage split-second choices during combat - do you conserve ammo in case you need it later, or go wild and hope to keep up the train of destruction? Except if you try to convserve ammo, the way the drop system works means you'll actually see less ammo and health.So, trying to learn how to play Nuclear Throne boils down to learning unintuitive, counter-productive and bizarre systems running under the hood. The game is fun for as long as you think that you're losing because you're playing badly or learning and not that the game itself is designed really weirdly.Finally, the game itself has an issue with procedural generation. Each level is generated, but ultimately they all feel the same. You'll be playing through the desert world a lot, either because each time you die while learning something (like how to beat Lil' Hunter) you need to pass through it, or because to reach the late game looping you just have to kill ten minutes to beat the pre-loop. Either way, it starts to get tiresome. The reason it gets tiresome is because in those first few levels there is no real choice to be made. Mutation choice is a moot point because there's a very clear flowchart to picking the superior ones, every time. Either you're experienced and pick the best mutation for your situation, or you aren't and it'll screw you until you learn what mutations the game rewards you for picking.The reason why procedural games like Isaac work is because the part of the game you'll play the most (the beginning) actively influences the later stages of the game. If you take red heart damage in Basement Two, you can lose a devil deal, which could drastically affect that run. In Nuclear Throne, getting shot early on doesn't matter. Nothing matters, really.At the end of the day, I recommended this game to all of my friends. I got over 400 hours of fun out of it before I grew to hate it. Someone else got 127 hours, another got 8, another got 24, another got 15 hours, yet another 240. Whether that is worth the money is up to the reader. I suggest buying Caves of Qud instead, if you're looking for a punishing game that respects the player."
